{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "Neutrinoless double beta decay is a lepton number violating process whose observation would also establish that neutrinos are their own anti-particles. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "There are many experimental efforts with a variety of techniques. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "Some (EXO, Kamland-Zen, GERDA phase I and CANDLES) started take data in 2011 and EXO has reported the first measurement of the half life for the double beta decay with two neutrinos of 136 Xe. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The sensitivities of the different proposals are reviewed.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "For many isotopes like 76 Ge \u03b2 decay is energetically forbidden, but double beta decay (2\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2) is allowed (A, Z) \u2192 (A, Z + 2) + 2e \u2212 + 2\u03bd e (1) This was suggested very early [1] and -following the idea of Majorana that neutrinos could be their own anti-particle [2] -also the possibility of neutrinoless double beta decay 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 was anticipated shortly afterwards [3] (for a review see [4,5]). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 139,
                    "end": 142,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "(1)"
                },
                {
                    "start": 173,
                    "end": 176,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 261,
                    "end": 264,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "[2]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 361,
                    "end": 364,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 383,
                    "end": 386,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[4,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 386,
                    "end": 388,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "5]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The latter case is very interesting since lepton number is violated and it would establish that the neutrino is its own anti-particle.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The experimental signature in this case is a line at the Q \u03b2\u03b2 value of the decay if the sum of the electron energies is plotted.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Searches for double beta decay date back to the beginning of nuclear physics and nowadays more than a dozen large scale experimental programs are suggested. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "These programs are compared in this article and also the status of theoretical matrix element calculations is discussed. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "For general reviews the reader is refered to the literature, e.g. [6,7,8].",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 66,
                    "end": 69,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[6,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 69,
                    "end": 71,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "7,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 71,
                    "end": 73,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "There are also other related processes like double positron decay or double electron capture processes. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "While 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 is already a suppressed process, the other decays are expected to be even rarer unless there is some resonance enhancement [9,10,11,12]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 134,
                    "end": 137,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[9,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 137,
                    "end": 140,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "10,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 140,
                    "end": 143,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "11,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 143,
                    "end": 146,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this article only 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 decay searches are discussed.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Motivation",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The observation of neutrino oscillation establishes that these particles have mass [13]. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 83,
                    "end": 87,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[13]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Since neutrinos have no electric charge, there is no known symmetry which forbids additional terms in the effective Lagrangian beside the standard Dirac mass term m D [7]:",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 167,
                    "end": 170,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "arXiv:1201.4916v1 [hep-ex] 24 Jan 2012",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The subscript L stands for the left-handed chiral field \u03bd L = 2 (1 \u2212 \u03b3 5 ) \u03bd and R for the righthanded projection 1 2 (1 + \u03b3 5 ) \u03bd. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The superscript C denotes charge conjugation. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The m R term describes therefore an incoming neutrino and an outgoing anti-neutrino, i.e. lepton number is violated by 2 units. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The eigen states of the mass matrix are of the form (\u03bd + \u03bd c ). ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Consequently neutrinos are expected to be -in general -their own anti-particles, i.e. Majorana particles.",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "What is the best experimental approach to establish that our known neutrinos are Majorana particles? ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Neutrinos (or anti-neutrinos) are produced in charged weak current reactions and -depending on the charge of the associated lepton -only one chiral projection couples. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "For example in \u03b2 decay n \u2192 p e \u2212\u03bd e,R , a right-handed anti-neutrino couples:",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Here, U is the PMNS mixing matrix, \u03bd i are the mass eigen states with mass eigen values m i , E",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "is the neutrino energy and h stands for the helicity of the anti-neutrino.",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "For a Dirac particle these anti-neutrinos can only undergo detection reactions like p\u03bd e,R \u2192 n e + . ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "If, on the other hand, neutrinos are Majorana particles, then the \u03bd i,h=\u22121 component can undergo the reaction \u03bd e,L n \u2192 p e \u2212 with \u03bd e,L = 1",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The rate of this reaction 1 is however suppressed by the factor (m i /E) 2 which is e.g. 10 \u221214 for a neutrino mass of 0.1 eV and a neutrino energy of 1 MeV. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus solar neutrino experiments for example will not be able to establish the nature of neutrinos.",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The alternative is the search for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 where the neutrino only enters as a propagator  [16]. ",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 87,
                    "end": 91,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b15",
                    "text": "[16]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Clearly this needs independent confirmation which poses another motivation for the experimental efforts.",
            "section": "Motivation",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Experimental sensitivity",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "An experiment will observe some background events \u03bb bkg which -if this number scales by the detector mass M -is given by",
            "section": "Experimental sensitivity",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "and possibly signal events",
            "section": "Experimental sensitivity",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Here t is the measurement time, B the so called background index given typical in cnts/(keV\u2022kg\u2022y), \u2206E is the width of the search window which depends on the experimental energy resolution, N A is the Avogadro constant, the signal detection efficiency, \u03b7 the mass fraction of the 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 isotope, A the molar mass of this isotope and T 0\u03bd 1/2 its half life. ",
            "section": "Experimental sensitivity",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "If systematic errors become important e.g. if the energy resolution is not well known or the assumption of the background shape is not correct, then the sensitivity is reduced.",
            "section": "Experimental sensitivity",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Theoretical considerations",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The half life for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 is given by [7] [",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 35,
                    "end": 38,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Here G 0\u03bd is the calculable phase space factor (Tab. 1), m e is the electron mass and M 0\u03bd is the nuclear matrix element whose calculation is difficult and can only be done using approximations.",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "For a review see for example [6,8].",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 29,
                    "end": 32,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[6,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 32,
                    "end": 34,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "While the observation of 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 would manifest lepton number violation and the neutrino's Majorana nature, the underlying physics can only be disclosed if the observed T 0\u03bd 1/2 for different isotopes and possibly other variables like the angle between the emitted electrons is compared to theory. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Consequently, there is a large interest in nuclear matrix element calculations and substantial progress has been made during the last years. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Traditionally, nuclear shell model (NSM) and quasi particle random phase approximation (QRPA) calculations have been performed. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Recently new approaches like the interacting boson model (IBM), the generating coordinate model (GCM) and the projected Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov (pHFB) method have been applied. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "A discussion of these calculations is given in [27].",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 47,
                    "end": 51,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b26",
                    "text": "[27]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The results of these calculations are shown in Fig. 1. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 47,
                    "end": 53,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The following statements can be made concerning the status:",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 There is no large variation for the NME between the different isotopes. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "This might be due to the fact that only neighboring neutrons in a nucleus contribute to the decay [17,20].",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 98,
                    "end": 102,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b16",
                    "text": "[17,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 102,
                    "end": 105,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b19",
                    "text": "20]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 For the NSM, all values are systematically lower than for other methods. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 10,
                    "end": 13,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "NSM",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Possible reasons for this effect are discussed in the literature [17,28].",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 65,
                    "end": 69,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b16",
                    "text": "[17,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 69,
                    "end": 72,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b27",
                    "text": "28]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The differences between the QRPA calculations of different groups are now quite small. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 1. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Figure 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Left: Different calculations for nuclear matrix elements for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 decay for light neutrino exchange. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "NSM = Nuclear shell model [17,18], SRQRPA = self-consistent renormalized quasi-particle random phase approximation [19,20,21] (matrix elements are scaled by 1.14 to compensate for different phase space factors), pnQRPA = proton-neutron quasi particle random phase approximation [22], GCM = generating coordinate method [23], IBM = interacting boson model [24,25] (matrix elements are scaled by 1.18 to estimate the effect if the UCOM short range correlation instead of the Jastrow type would have been used [8]), pHBF= projected Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov model [26]. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
