            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Right: ratio of expected 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 events per kg target mass for the different models normalized to 130 Te.",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 For a given isotope the calculations spread by typically a factor of 2, i.e. a factor of 4 for",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The role of short range correlations has been studied and the UCOM correction has emerged as standard [29]. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 104,
                    "end": 108,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b28",
                    "text": "[29]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Alternatively, a self consistent implementation was first applied to SRQRPA [20] and later to other methods [18,26] and resulted in small changes.",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 76,
                    "end": 80,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b19",
                    "text": "[20]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 108,
                    "end": 112,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b17",
                    "text": "[18,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 112,
                    "end": 115,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b25",
                    "text": "26]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 69,
                    "end": 76,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "SRQRPA",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Experimental input can have a large shift of the result. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "For example charge exchange reaction measurements of 150 Nd( 3 He,t) and 150 Sm(t, 3 He) [30] result in a quenching factor of 0.75 for the g A coupling and hence a reduction of the matrix element by 25% for 150 Nd [21]. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 89,
                    "end": 93,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b29",
                    "text": "[30]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 214,
                    "end": 218,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b20",
                    "text": "[21]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this calculation, deformation was treated for the first time in a QRPA calculation.",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "For 76 Ge and 76 Se, the proton and neutron valence orbital occupancies have been measured [31,32]. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 30,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 91,
                    "end": 95,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b30",
                    "text": "[31,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 95,
                    "end": 98,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b31",
                    "text": "32]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "If the models are adjusted to reproduce these values, the NSM result increases by 15% [18] while the QRPA results are reduced by about 20% [33,34]. ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 30,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 86,
                    "end": 90,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b17",
                    "text": "[18]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 139,
                    "end": 143,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b32",
                    "text": "[33,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 143,
                    "end": 146,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b33",
                    "text": "34]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Hence the difference between NSM and QRPA becomes half as large.",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 30,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The calculations are performed for the standard light neutrino exchange but results for other mechanisms like SUSY particle exchange are also available [35,19].",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 31,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 152,
                    "end": 156,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b34",
                    "text": "[35,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 156,
                    "end": 159,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b18",
                    "text": "19]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In order to see whether some isotopes are better suited for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 decay searches from a theoretical point of view, the number of expected decays per isotope mass can be compared.",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 32,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "This value includes the phase space factor, the matrix element and the mass number A. For the comparison it is sufficient to look at the ratio of decay rates and in this case, some of the systematic effects of the matrix element calculations cancel since there are typically correlations ",
            "section": "Theoretical considerations",
            "paragraph_rank": 33,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Comparison of experiments",
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The experiments searching for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 decay use a large variety of detection mechanisms and background reduction methods, see Tab. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 123,
                    "end": 127,
                    "type": "table",
                    "text": "Tab."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "2. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The current status of almost all of them is described in these proceedings. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Therefore a more detailed discussion is omitted here. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Instead the key performance numbers are taken for a comparison of the sensitivities of some experiments.",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Since experiments use different isotopes a relative scaling factor for the different matrix elements and phase spaces has to be applied. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "This factor can be estimated using If the number of background events is large, equation 8 can be used to estimate the experimental sensitivity. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "A relative figure-of-merit can then be defined as",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "One can call this the \"ultimate\" relative sensitivity of an experiment. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Tab. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "3 lists the Table 3. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 12,
                    "end": 19,
                    "type": "table",
                    "text": "Table 3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Comparison of figure-of-merits (FOM) for the case of large number of background events (\"ultimate sensitivity\"). ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "f A is the scale factor for a given isotope taken from Fig. 1(right), and \u2206E is the energy window which is taken here to be 1(2) full width half maximum for experiments with > 0.5% (< 0.5%) resolution. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 55,
                    "end": 68,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1(right)"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Note that the efficiency is reduced by 0. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Alternatively, the (relative) sensitivity vs. time can be estimated from equation 7 b\u0177",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Here \u03a8(\u03bb bkg ) is the \"average\" 90%C.L. upper limit of the number of signal events for \u03bb bkg background events calculated according to the method discussed in [29]. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 37,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 159,
                    "end": 163,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b28",
                    "text": "[29]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The result is shown in \u2022 If one takes the spread of the data points in Fig. 1 the factor f A has a \u2248 20% uncertainty.",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 37,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 71,
                    "end": 77,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The 2\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 background is irreducible and can only be avoided with an energy resolution \u03c3 < 1 \u2212 2% at Q \u03b2\u03b2 . ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 38,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "This requirement depends of course strongly on T 2\u03bd 1/2 which varies by a factor of 300 for the isotopes considered. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 38,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "For some experiments this background is not fully taken into account for the background index.",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 38,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 All sensitivities given are the scales for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 discovery. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 39,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "To get relative sensitivities for m \u03b2\u03b2 the square root has to be taken.",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 39,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Of the running experiments, Kamland-Zen should have the largest potential. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 40,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 30,
                    "end": 42,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Kamland-Zen",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This is impressive if one takes into account that it was not specially built for this physics.",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 40,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Germanium experiments can be very competitive despite the fact that the phase space factor is so small. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 41,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Especially if a positive signal will be claimed, a narrow peak at Q \u03b2\u03b2 will be more convincing than a broad shoulder. ",
            "section": "Comparison of experiments",
            "paragraph_rank": 41,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Summary",
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Neutrinoless double beta decay is the best experimentally accessible method to test whether neutrinos are Majorana particles. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 42,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "This decay violates lepton number and is therefore on equal footing to proton decay searches. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 42,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The motivation for several large efforts in this field is therefore obvious.",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 42,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "For a long time, the Heidelberg-Moscow experiment has dominated the field and its claim of a 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 signal has not been scrutinized since 2001. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 43,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "In 2011, EXO, Kamland-Zen, CANDLES and GERDA-I started to take data. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 43,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 27,
                    "end": 35,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "CANDLES",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s4"
                },
                {
                    "start": 39,
                    "end": 45,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "GERDA-",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s5"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "All but CANDLES are more sensitive than Heidelberg-Moscow and especially Kamland-Zen is expected to answer this question in the next 12 months. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 43,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 8,
                    "end": 16,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "CANDLES",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s6"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "EXO has already reported a first time measurement of T 2\u03bd 1/2 ( 136 Xe) = 2.11 \u00b1 0.04(stat) \u00b1 0.21(syst) \u2022 10 21 y which is considerably lower than previous limits [15].",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 43,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 164,
                    "end": 168,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "[15]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Beyond this next step, experiments want to explore the m \u03b2\u03b2 region for the inverted neutrino mass hierarchy. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 44,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "This will eventually require ton scale experiments. ",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 44,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Which of the proposed solutions will be built is open at the moment.",
            "section": "Summary",
            "paragraph_rank": 44,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig. 1 .",
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "The values used here are f A (Ge) = 0.35, f A (Se) = 1.1, f A (Mo) = 1.6, f A (Te) = 1, f A (Xe) = 0.55 and f A (Nd) = 2.2.",
            "section": "Fig. 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 45,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig 2 .",
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig 2. ",
            "section": "Fig 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 46,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Here all experiments are assumed to start at time 0. ",
            "section": "Fig 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 46,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "A few comments should be made concerning the interpretation of Tab. ",
            "section": "Fig 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 46,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "3 and Fig. 2.",
            "section": "Fig 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 46,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 2 .",
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022",
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 2. ",
            "section": "Figure 2 .\u2022",
            "paragraph_rank": 47,
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "Relative experimental sensitivity for 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 life time limit versus running time.",
            "section": "Figure 2 .\u2022",
            "paragraph_rank": 47,
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "The coupling strength m \u03b2\u03b2 is called the effective Majorana mass.",
            "paragraph_rank": 48,
            "section_rank": 11
        },
        {
            "text": "Table 1 .",
            "section_rank": 12
        },
        {
            "text": "List of most interesting 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 isotopes. ",
            "section": "Table 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 49,
            "section_rank": 12
        },
        {
            "text": "Half lives are taken from[14,15] while all other numbers are from[7].",
            "section": "Table 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 49,
            "section_rank": 12,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 25,
                    "end": 29,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[14,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 29,
                    "end": 32,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "15]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 65,
                    "end": 68,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "If \u03bb bkg < 1 the experimental sensitivity scales with M \u2022 t while for \u03bb bkg >> 1 the e.g. 90% C.L. limit on the half life (assuming there is no signal) is given by",
            "section": "Table 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 50,
            "section_rank": 12
        },
        {
            "text": "Table 2 .",
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "Selection of 0\u03bd\u03b2\u03b2 experiments. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 51,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "The right hand plot of Fig 1 shows these ratios for the different models normalized to the decay rate of 130 Te. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 51,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "One sees that 76 Ge is less favorable. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 51,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "The expected decays per kg vary between 20% and 50% of the rate of 130 Te. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 51,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "In other words: if all experimental parameters were the same then one would need a factor of \u22483 more target mass in a 76 Ge experiment to have the same sensitivity. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 51,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "In reality this is not the case, i.e. the superior energy resolution of Ge detectors compensates this effect.",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 51,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "Since the charge of the outgoing lepton is the same as in the production process, U and not U * enters here.",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 52,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "A fiducial volume cut will reduce the active mass. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 53,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "Depending on whether the background index is normalized to the total mass or to the fiducial mass, the efficiency has to go under the square root or not. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 53,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "The meaning of B is not always clearly defined in the literature. ",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 53,
            "section_rank": 13
        },
        {
            "text": "Here the normalization to the total mass is assumed.",
            "section": "Table 2 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 53,
            "section_rank": 13
        }
    ]
